The measurements were conducted at the Joint Institute for Nuclear Research (JINR) in Dubna, specifically in the Cyclotron Laboratory (CYCLONE), using a proton energy of 1 GeV. The experiment aimed to investigate the production of mesons in the government reaction of relativistic protons on HM Ta (reaction, π+). The experimental setup included two scintillation detectors, S1 and S2, for registering particles emitted into the forward hemisphere, and three scintillation detectors, S3-S5, for measuring the corresponding angular distributions in the study. The obtained results were compared with those based on the response developed by AJ.

**Introduction**  
Meson production is one of the most significant phenomena in hadronic interactions, playing a crucial role in fields such as astrophysics, cosmic ray physics, and accelerator technology. Here, we present data on meson production from the collision of relativistic protons with tantalum (reaction, π+) in federal collisions. These experiments were conducted at the CYCLONE laboratory of JINR.

**Experimental Setup**  
The experimental setup used in our experiment includes:
- Two scintillation detectors, S1 and S2;
- Three scintillation detectors;
- An improved collimator;
- A target made of 0.1 mm thick tantalum foil;
- A detection system composed of four scintillation detectors, T1-T4.

